GPA Prediction Model Development¶

In this notebook, we attempt to develop a Machine Learning Model that can effectively predict one's GPA primarily using sklearn

In [2]:
def rmspe(y_true, y_pred):
    error = np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(((y_true - y_pred) / y_true))))
    return error

rmspe_scorer = make_scorer(
    rmspe,
    greater_is_better=False
)

Dataset¶

The dataset we'll use comes from the Student Alcohol Consumption dataset. Link

The metadata can be found in data/metadata.txt.

Feature Variables¶

  • school - student's school (binary: 'GP' - Gabriel Pereira or 'MS' - Mousinho da Silveira)
  • sex - student's sex (binary: 'F' - female or 'M' - male)
  • age - student's age (numeric: from 15 to 22)
  • address - student's home address type (binary: 'U' - urban or 'R' - rural)
  • famsize - family size (binary: 'LE3' - less or equal to 3 or 'GT3' - greater than 3)
  • Pstatus - parent's cohabitation status (binary: 'T' - living together or 'A' - apart)
  • Medu - mother's education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 – 5th to 9th grade, 3 – secondary education or 4 – higher education)
  • Fedu - father's education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 – 5th to 9th grade, 3 – secondary education or 4 – higher education)
  • Mjob - mother's job (nominal: 'teacher', 'health' care related, civil 'services' (e.g. administrative or police), 'at_home' or 'other')
  • Fjob - father's job (nominal: 'teacher', 'health' care related, civil 'services' (e.g. administrative or police), 'at_home' or 'other')
  • reason - reason to choose this school (nominal: close to 'home', school 'reputation', 'course' preference or 'other')
  • guardian - student's guardian (nominal: 'mother', 'father' or 'other')
  • traveltime - home to school travel time (numeric: 1 - <15 min., 2 - 15 to 30 min., 3 - 30 min. to 1 hour, or 4 - >1 hour)
  • studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
  • failures - number of past class failures (numeric: n if 1<=n<3, else 4)
  • schoolsup - extra educational support (binary: yes or no)
  • famsup - family educational support (binary: yes or no)
  • paid - extra paid classes within the course subject (Math or Portuguese) (binary: yes or no)
  • activities - extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no)
  • nursery - attended nursery school (binary: yes or no)
  • higher - wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)
  • internet - Internet access at home (binary: yes or no)
  • romantic - with a romantic relationship (binary: yes or no)
  • famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)
  • freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)
  • absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)
  • These grades are related with the course subject, Math or Portuguese:

Target Variable¶

  • G1 - first period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  • G2 - second period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  • G3 - final grade (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)

Are there duplicate rows in the datasets?¶

Next, we want to determine if there are duplicate rows in the datasets. This is a concern as if there are duplicate rows, data leakage into the test and validation dataset are highly likely, leading to us developing a data-leakage-affected model.

Feature Engineering¶

Students scoring 0¶

Firstly, we observed that students scored 0 in certain grades. It is very unlikely that students scored 0, and more likely that they left school or changed school during that time, and as such the assessment did not capture their performance. As such we'll average across grades where the grade isn't 0.

In [16]:
# As we have observed from EDA, it is unlikely
def calc_grade(df_pass):
	df = df_pass.copy()
	# df = df.apply(lambda x: x.max(axis=0), axis=1)
	count = df.apply(lambda x: int(x['G1'] > 0) + int(x['G2'] > 0) + int(x['G3'] > 0), axis=1)
	df = df.sum(axis=1) / count
	return df

grades_train = calc_grade(y_train)
grades_test = calc_grade(y_test)

20 point system to 4.0 GPA¶

Next, we need to convert from this 20 point system to the Polytechnic 4.0 GPA system. However, as we do not know the Polytechnic bell curve, we'll take inspiration from the Singapore Management University system and adapt it to fit the 4.0 GPA system.

In [17]:
def to_percentile(series):
	return series.apply(lambda x: percentileofscore(sorted(series), x))

# NUS Bell Curve formula taken from https://blog.nus.edu.sg/provost/2012/01/20/the-bell-curve/
percentile_reg = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators = 1000)
percentile = np.array([0.0016, 0.0016, 0.0016, 0.0381, 0.1397, 0.1794, 0.2048, 0.1921, 0.1429, 0.0698, 0.0286])
percentile = np.cumsum(percentile)
gpa = np.array([0, 1.0, 1.3, 2.0, 2.4, 2.7, 3.0, 3.3, 3.7, 4, 4])
percentile_reg.fit(percentile.reshape((-1, 1)), gpa)

def percentile_to_gpa(percentile):
	if len(percentile.shape) == 1:
		percentile = percentile.values.reshape((-1, 1))
	return percentile_reg.predict(percentile / 100)
In [18]:
y_train = percentile_to_gpa(to_percentile(grades_train))
y_test = percentile_to_gpa(to_percentile(grades_test))

def show_learning_curve(model, X, y, ax):
    folds = 3
    train_size, train_scores, valid_scores = learning_curve(model, X, y, train_sizes=np.linspace(0.1,1,5), scoring='neg_mean_absolute_percentage_error', cv=folds)
    size = np.repeat(train_size, repeats=folds)
    train_score = train_scores.flatten()
    test_score = valid_scores.flatten()
    df = pd.DataFrame({
        'Train Size': size, 'Train Scores': train_score, 'Test Scores': test_score
    })
    new_df = df.melt(['Train Size'])
    new_df = new_df.sort_values(by=['Train Size', 'variable'], ascending=[True, False])
    new_df.columns = ['Train Size', 'Type', 'Error (MAPE)']
    sns.lineplot(data=new_df, x='Train Size', y='Error (MAPE)', hue='Type', ax=ax, palette=sns.color_palette()[0:2])
    ax.set_title('Learning Curve')

def show_scatter(y_true, y_pred, scatterAx):
    flat_y_true = np.array(y_true).flatten()
    flat_y_pred = y_pred.flatten()
    sns.scatterplot(x=flat_y_true, y=y_pred, ax=scatterAx)
    limits = [0, max(max(flat_y_true), max(flat_y_pred))]
    scatterAx.set_title('Prediction Scatterplot')
    scatterAx.set_xlabel('True GPA')
    scatterAx.set_ylabel('Predicted GPA')
    scatterAx.plot(limits, limits, color=sns.color_palette('Set2')[1])

def get_model_performance(y_true, y_pred, y_train_pred, model_name, train_scores=True):
    flat_y_true = np.array(y_true).flatten()
    flat_y_pred = y_pred.flatten()
    flat_y_train_pred = y_train_pred.flatten()

    metrics = {
        'Train RMSPE': rmspe(flat_y_true, flat_y_train_pred),
        'Test RMSPE': rmspe(flat_y_true, flat_y_pred),
        'Train MAE': mae(flat_y_true, flat_y_train_pred),
        'Test MAE': mae(flat_y_true, flat_y_pred),
        'Train MAPE': mape(flat_y_true, flat_y_train_pred),
        'Test MAPE': mape(flat_y_true, flat_y_pred)
    }

    return pd.DataFrame([metrics], index=[model_name])

def assess_model(model, X, y, name=None, plot_show = True):
    if (name == None):
        name = type(model).__name__
    if plot_show:
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
        fig.suptitle(name, fontsize=15)

        subplots = fig.subplots(1, 2)
        ax = subplots[0]


        scatterAx = subplots[1]
        scatterAx.axis('equal')
    
    if plot_show:
        show_learning_curve(model, X, y, ax)
        ax.set_ylim(-1, 0)

    test_predictions = cross_val_predict(model, X, y, cv=5)

    model_copy = clone(model)
    model_copy.fit(X, y)
    train_predictions = model_copy.predict(X)


    if plot_show:
        show_scatter(y, test_predictions, scatterAx)
    model_performance = get_model_performance(y, test_predictions, train_predictions, name)

    if plot_show:
        display(model_performance)
        plt.show()

    return model_performance

def show_summary(summary, train=False):

    train_columns = [column for column in summary.columns if 'Train' in column]
    test_columns = [column for column in summary.columns if 'Test' in column]

    df = summary.copy()
    if (not train):
        df.drop(train_columns, inplace=True, axis=1)

    return df.sort_values(by=test_columns)

Model Improvement¶

Now we can focus on improving our model. We see that the models HistGradientBoosting, Extreme Gradient Boosting and Random Forest are all strong base models.

In [37]:
base_models = [HistGradientBoostingRegressor, XGBRegressor, RandomForestRegressor]

Log Transforming the Target¶

We'll try log transforming the target

In [38]:
transform_models = {}
names = ["HGB", "XGB", "RF"]

for i, model in enumerate(base_models):
    transform_models[f'LTT + {names[i]}'] = TransformedTargetRegressor(
            model(random_state = random_state),
            func = np.log1p,
            inverse_func = np.expm1
        )

MinMax LogTransforming Target¶

Another method of log transforming the target is performing MinMax LogTransforming the target.

In [39]:
from utils import TwoTransformers

for i, model in enumerate(base_models):
    transform_models[f'MMLTT + {names[i]}'] = TransformedTargetRegressor(
            model(random_state = random_state),
            transformer=TwoTransformers()
        )

Hyperparameter tuning¶

Now that we have established the best combination of transformers and base model to use, we now move on to hyperparameter tuning.

In [42]:
if False:
	params = {
		'regressor__max_iter': np.arange(50, 550, 50),
		'regressor__max_leaf_nodes': np.arange(5, 55, 10),
		'regressor__max_depth': [None] + np.arange(5, 17, 2).tolist(),
		'regressor__min_samples_leaf': [20],
		'regressor__l2_regularization': [1, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0],
		'regressor__max_bins': np.arange(50, 255, 10),
		'regressor__early_stopping': [False, True, 'auto'],
	}

	mmltt_hgb = TransformedTargetRegressor(
			HistGradientBoostingRegressor(random_state = random_state),
			transformer=TwoTransformers()
		)

	cv = RandomizedSearchCV(mmltt_hgb, params, n_iter=1000, random_state=random_state, n_jobs = -1, refit = False)

	preprocess = Pipeline(steps=[
		('column_fix', ColumnFixer()),
		('preprocessing', CategoricalOHE),
		('scaler', StandardScaler()),
	])

	cv.fit(preprocess.fit_transform(X_train[keep_cols]), y_train)
	cv.best_params_

Feature Importance¶

We'll determine the feature importance, so that we can determine which columns are useful in predicting and which are not. This will allow us to minimize the number of questions we have to ask the user.

In [44]:
preprocess = Pipeline(steps=[
	('preprocessing', CategoricalOHE),
	('scaler', StandardScaler()),
])

final = Pipeline([
	('preprocess', preprocess),
	('model', model)
])

final.fit(X_train[keep_cols], y_train)
print("MAE:",mae(final.predict(X_test[keep_cols]), y_test))

feat_imp = permutation_importance(final, X_test[keep_cols], y_test, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_percentage_error', random_state=random_state, n_repeats=2)
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 18))
ax = fig.subplots()
sorted_importances = feat_imp.importances_mean.argsort()
sorted_importances = sorted_importances.tolist()[::-1]
total = feat_imp.importances_mean.sum()
mean_imp = feat_imp.importances_mean / total
sns.barplot(x=mean_imp[sorted_importances], y=np.arange(len(X_test[keep_cols].columns)), orient='h', ax=ax, palette=sns.color_palette("mako", n_colors=len(X_test[keep_cols].columns)))
ax.set_yticklabels(X_test[keep_cols].columns[sorted_importances])
ax.set_title("Feature Importance of Final Model\nFormat: <cumulative> | <individual>", fontsize=15)

cumsum = mean_imp[sorted_importances].cumsum()
[ax.text(mean_imp[sorted_importances][i] + float(ax.get_xlim()[1]) * 0.01, i + 0.05, f"{min(100, cumsum[i] * 100):.2f}% | {mean_imp[sorted_importances][i] * 100:.2f}%") for i in range(len(X_test[keep_cols].columns))]
ax.set_xlim(0, ax.set_xlim()[1] * 1.3)

plt.show()
